{"ts":"2026-06-27T17:04:32.120Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Client ID Mapping**\n\nI've been looking at the governance mock data in `lib/api-auth.ts`, specifically examining how `client_id` is assigned. It appears that `gov-001` and `gov-002` both link to `client-001`, and `gov-003` is tied to `client-004`. The details of gov-004 will be determined next.\n\n\n**Mapping Governance Items Dynamically**\n\nI've realized the `/api/v1/governance` endpoint automatically filters by the logged-in user's client association. For example, \"Apex Sovereign Group\" only gets `gov-001` and `gov-002`. I'm starting to think about how these filtered governance records can dynamically populate the `policies` and `oversights` states in the pages. I'm checking if a single governance item can be parsed to both, and examining the required structure for `policies`.\n\n\n**Refining Data Structures**\n\nI'm now comparing the `Governance` interface with the incoming `ApiGovernanceItem`. Initially, I thought they might be combined, but I'm leaning toward separating them. I'm considering whether to map or transform `ApiGovernanceItem` to fit the `Governance` structure. There may be some overlap in the fields, for example, `severity` and `status` could map to `status` and `status` respectively, although the types may need alignment.\n\n\n**Reconciling Governance Data**\n\nI'm now diving deeper into how to populate both `policies` and `oversights` from `/api/v1/governance`. I've analyzed the `OversightItem` and `DocItem` interfaces, and I think it might be possible to construct both lists dynamically from the backend data. I'm exploring whether governance items can be categorized and mapped to the appropriate state.\n\n\n"}}
