{"ts":"2026-06-27T17:04:43.059Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Connecting APIs**\n\nOkay, so I see a standard `documents` API, which is a good starting point. Now, the task is clear. I need to connect `/portal/analytics` to `/api/v1/analytics/client` and `/portal/governance` to `/api/v1/governance`. The plan involves replacing static data with backend summaries and governance records. I can do this.\n\n\n**Analyzing Governance Endpoint**\n\nI'm now diving deeper into the `/api/v1/governance` endpoint. It seems to provide a combined list of all governance items, which I'll need to sort into \"policies\" and \"oversights\" categories. I have to look at the response, like `gov-001`, to understand how to map these items to the three tabs on the governance page (policies, oversights, and docs). My focus is now on ensuring that the endpoint integration aligns with the existing visual design (Phase 4), including charts, filters, and mobile responsiveness, while also accounting for loading, empty, error, and retry states.\n\n\n**Categorizing Governance Items**\n\nI'm now investigating specific fields within the governance data. I've noted how the `standard` field (like ISO-27001) can reliably indicate a policy check. Then, I am focusing on the `status` field, particularly \"pending\", \"approved\", or \"rejected\", which suggests oversight items. Now, I am planning to map these items dynamically from the backend endpoint. Currently, I am analyzing `DEFAULT_API_MOCK_GOVERNANCE` from `lib/api-auth.ts`, looking at the items and their attributes. I'll dynamically determine how to render each item.\n\n\n"}}
